@NODE "AmiEmul" "Emulation, How?"
@font xen.font 8

  @{b}@{u}Emulation@{uu}@{ub}

  The emulation option is under great debate, if the new AmigaOS etc etc is
 to support 3.1- code, then emulation must be done.  However what type of
 emulation is the question.  I'm going to try and explain the 2 main
 types that are supported at the moment. (This section is'nt finished yet
 as there is so much to add etc)

  @{b}@{u}Internal Emulation@{uu}@{ub}

  This is where the OS itself emulates the older code.  Similar to the
 MacOS system on the PowerMAC platform.

  @{fg highlight}Good things:@{fg text}  -Simple for the user
                -Transparent to the user
                -Incorporated into the OS allowing very little user
                 interaction to get running.               

  @{fg highlight}Bad things:@{fg text}  -Hard to upgrade if OS in ROM
               -Makes OS's kernel even more complex
               -Conflictions possible inside the OS since older software wouldn't 
                use the same memory system (Assuming the 1 memory type is
                introduced. Also memory protection etc will make the
                emulation process harder.

  @{b}@{u}External Emulation@{uu}@{ub}

  This is where the emulation is done by a separate program @{fg highlight}@{i}like@{ui}@{fg text}
 ShapeShifter however, it integrates the emulation a lot closer to the
 current OS than ShapeShifter does.  I use ShapeShifter as an example as I
 can not think of a system that is closer.

 @{fg highlight}Good things:@{fg text}  -Emulation can be improved fast since the program just needs
                to be replaced or patched.
               -Allows use of external hardware/software.  Example, drivers
                can be made to support the latest GFX card, or to use a new piece
                of graphics software.
               -Problems with memory protection are avoided since the
                applications are in an emulated environment.

 @{fg highlight}Bad things:@{fg text}  -The simple fact you have to load another program :)
              -Separate resources for the 2 different sides (Old OS and
               New).

 @{b}So, do you have any comments or anything you want added?
 @{"Mail me" Link "AmiAuthor"} and I'll be happy to put it in.@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AmiFami" "Future Jobs For The Amiga"
@font xen.font 8

  @{b}@{u}Future Jobs For The Amiga@{uu}@{ub}

  When the Amiga was first released some 10+ years ago, it opened new areas
 that computers could be used in, multimedia for an example.  For a hold on
 the future the Amiga needs to once again grab a hold of a new and
 inovative market, and this is one of the challenges ahead of us.  This
 section is basically for new ideas where the Amiga could be used in new ways
 to once again be a pioneer in the computing world.

 @{b}Entertainment Networks (EN):@{ub}

  With the introduction of DVDs (Digital Video Discs) and Set-Top boxs, the 
 computer is going to move away from being the white box we know, to a black 
 addon for your TV and Stereo making it just another peice of entertainment
 hardware as common as a video recorder.  The worlds largest computer
 powers are saying the next big computer battle ground will be over EN
 systems which are expected to be in almost every home in 10 years time.

  A EN would basically consist of a TV, and DVD system all connected to a
 computer network.  This computer network would be run with a server hidden
 away out of site doing the main processing and other tasks while being
 connected to terminals around the house such as Set-Top boxs, and computer
 remotes.  From these terminals you will be able to control everything from
 taping your favorite TV programs to reading your email.

  With the Amigas talent for being powerful even with low reasources, the
 Amiga would be perfect for the EN idea.  Current estimated prices on a
 Set-Top box using current PC technology is between $2500US and $4000US
 which is far out of the reach of an average family.  However using Amiga
 technology, this would be possible at a fraction of the cost not to
 mention that EN systems could be made well within 2 years rather than the 
 10 years other companies such as MicroSoft are expecting.  However, just
 a Set-Top box is not the answer, the EN system would need a full computer
 system with advanced networking but still being cheap enough for home use.
 Can you imagine your Amiga running your houses security system?  This
 would all be possible via a EN system.

