@NODE "AmiWhat" "What Can We Do To Help Amiga"
@font xen.font 8

  @{b}@{u}What Now?@{uu}@{ub}

  Waiting and hopeing for a new machine is'nt going to make one magicly
 appear, we need to keep up the support for the Amigas we have for as long
 as possible to insure that there is enough support to allow us move to the
 new platform(s).  We can do this by setting ourselves some rough standards
 and by sticking to them.  I have looked round and heres an example. Im not
 saying this is right or even close, but I think its fair.

  At this time, I would consider the following to be an good example of an
 average machine which should be supported to the best people can manage.

 @{fg highlight}Graphics:@{fg text}@{b}AGA@{ub}

  AGA is now considered the minimum graphics system for the Amiga and
 should be supported.  64 colours should be the minimum that games are made
 in now, but of course 256+ would be prefered.

 @{fg highlight}CPU:@{fg text}@{b}EC030/50Mhz@{ub}
  
  A 50Mhz EC030 is considered the average CPU on Amigas now and should be
 used to their full ability, however the only things to do that half the
 time is Demos.  If coded well, a 030/50Mhz is more than capable of a great
 game or business aplication.  Also the 030 is a good example to use as it
 is now a cheap expansion card and isnt to far out of reach for everyday
 users.

  Even thought I class the 030/50 as standard, we should start making code
 for highend systems like the 040, using as much optimizations as
 possible. After all, the 040 can get large speed increases for 040
 optimized code, and I dont mean 882, but real 040 code.  e.g. The 020
 version of LZX on a 040/40Mhz is 3x faster than on a 030/50, but the 040
 version is 5x faster and more faster!  Some FPU programs get a 7x boost
 in speed from the 882 versions when 040 optimized, now thats what I call a
 worth while speed increase!

  @{fg highlight}Sound:@{fg text}@{b}Mixing@{ub}

  We all know the Amiga has wonderful 4 channel 8bit sound, however this
 just doesnt cut it in 97, but as we have little to use, we have to make
 the most of it.  Software exists today to provide 8+ channels via Mixing
 routines, which could be used in any games or demos, possibly altering 
 the sample rate depending on the speed of the CPU. The 030/50Mhz is 
 considered standard and it can easily cope with a good quality 8
 channel song.

  Also, 14bit routines have become more common now allowing higher sound
 quailty for sound.

 (I wrote this before AHI 4 was out, of course AHI needs some big fixes but
  its damn good for a start)

 @{fg highlight}Memory:@{fg text}@{b}2Megs Chip, 4Megs Fast@{ub}

  These days it is rare to find an Amiga with less ram than 2Megs Chip and
 4Megs fast and yet few game makers take advantage, this is something that
 needs to be changed.  People complain how games have cruddy graphics and
 badly sampled sound, what do expect if you are running a game that will
 work on a raw 1200!

 @{fg highlight}Expansion:@{fg text}

  The one area the above stats won't thrive in is 3D Texture mapping type
 applications, BUT there is now a low cost partial solution to the problem.
 Cards such as the 'Graffiti' remove the need for the complex and slow
 Chuncky to Plannar routines used in 3D games and programs such as TKG and
 Breathless for a low price.  Support for these cards is essential as they
 allow slower and cheaper cpus to achive what only faster and more expensive
 cpus have been able to do in the past.  One other benefit of these cards
 is that even ECS/OCS machines can use them and even display 256 colours on
 screen.  Of course, the c2p routines are starting to get realy good now,
 theres some 040 c2p routines that are almost AS fast as the Graffiti, and
 well, on an 060, take a guess.

 @{fg highlight}Software:@{fg text}

  Just above I stated a 3D type card should become standard, thats fine
 however I think that 3D software such as 3D games on the Amiga for now is a
 waste of programers time.  I'd rather play Dune fast on an 020 rather than
 play a Doom Clone at 10fps on a 040 ;).  Amigas cant be beaten for 2D
 games so why not get over the whole 3D idea and start making those games
 that the Amiga became famous for.

  But thats just games, what about business?  The Amiga is currently
 lacking business software, so this should be an area that needs to be
 addressed.  Software such as Word Processors, Data Bases, Multimedia
 Systems, Spread Sheets etc.

